  <section>
    <h2>Multiple Terms</h2>
    <p>Multiple <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code> elements can share a single <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> description. This is useful for synonyms, abbreviations, or alternate names.</p>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/dt-multiple-terms.html" url="dt-multiple-terms.html" title="Multiple terms" shadow></browser-window>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Multiple terms sharing description">{{ multipleTermsCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Term with Multiple Descriptions</h2>
    <p>A single <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code> can be followed by multiple <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> elements for terms with multiple meanings.</p>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Term with multiple descriptions">{{ multipleDescriptionsCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Rich Content in Terms</h2>
    <p>Definition terms can contain inline elements like <code>&lt;code&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;abbr&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;dfn&gt;</code>, or links.</p>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/dt-rich-content.html" url="dt-rich-content.html" title="Rich content in terms" shadow></browser-window>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Rich content in terms">{{ richContentCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <h3>Using dfn Element</h3>
    <p>For the defining instance of a term, wrap it in <code>&lt;dfn&gt;</code>:</p>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Using dfn inside dt">{{ dfnCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>

    <h3>Screen Reader Behavior</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Announced as a term or label within the definition list context</li>
      <li>Associated with following <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> elements</li>
      <li>Users can navigate between term-description pairs</li>
      <li>The bold styling helps sighted users identify terms</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Best Practices</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Keep terms concise and clear</li>
      <li>Ensure every <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code> has at least one associated <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code></li>
      <li>Consider using <code>&lt;dfn&gt;</code> inside <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code> for the defining instance of a term</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>CSS Properties</h2>

    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Property</th>
          <th>Value</th>
          <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>font-weight</code></td>
          <td><code>600</code></td>
          <td>Semi-bold to distinguish terms from descriptions</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>When a <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code> follows a <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> (starting a new term group), <code>dd + dt</code> adds <code>margin-block-start: var(--size-m)</code> for visual separation.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Content Model</h2>

    <h3>Permitted Content</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Flow content, but no <code>&lt;header&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code>, sectioning, or heading elements</li>
      <li>Inline elements: <code>&lt;a&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;abbr&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;code&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;dfn&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;em&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;strong&gt;</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Required Parent</h3>
    <p>Must be a child of <code>&lt;dl&gt;</code>, optionally inside a <code>&lt;dl-item&gt;</code>.</p>
  </section>

